The verb is here in subj. because this is oblique interrogation [5 149].—spolia opima. “ The honour-able spoi1s”; a term applied to the spoils taken by a Roman on the field of battle from the general of the enemy, whom he had conquered and elain. Livy mentions, in Bk. 1, ch. 10, that the spolia opima were only taken on three occasions during the existence of the Roman State. Romulus obtained them from the general of the Caeninenses; Aulus Cornelius Cossus, from Lar Tolumnius, king of the Veientes; Marcellus from Viridomarus, chieftain of the Insubrian Gauls.
